    rectoEn: 'The panel: "Explain QE to me in three sentences — without saying the word print."',
    versoEn: 'Reflex: "When the policy rate hits the zero bound while the Taylor rule prescribes a negative rate, the central bank buys long securities paid for with reserves: it swaps reserves for duration. It works through two channels — the signal, which makes the low-for-long promise credible, and duration scarcity, which compresses the term premium: the 10-year falls by about 50 to 100 bp for QE1. Reserves only circulate between banks: M0 swells, M2 does not move — which is why ten years of QE produced no inflation."',
