    rectoEn: 'Nowcasting: definition — and what GDPNow changes about reading GDP?',
    versoEn: 'The REAL-TIME estimate of a quantity published with a lag: quarterly GDP arrives a month after quarter-end, but its ingredients (retail sales, industrial production, external trade…) drop in continuously — a model like GDPNow (Atlanta Fed) aggregates them into an estimate updated at every release. Desk consequence: the official GDP print is often ALREADY IN THE PRICES via the nowcast — the "GDP surprise" plays out against the latest estimate, not against the previous quarter.',
